ning and normalization as specified per column, or where data quality issues are anticipated.\n\n**Foreign Key Resolution Strategy:**\n\n-   `Account.Id` (target) <- `kunden.kunden_nr` (source)\n-   `Contact.AccountId` (target) <- `ansprechpartner.kunde` (source, maps to `kunden.kunden_nr`)\n-   `Opportunity.AccountId` (target) <- `chancen.kd_nr` (source, maps to `kunden.kunden_nr`)\n-   `Project__c.Account__c` (target) <- `proj.kd` (source, maps to `kunden.kunden_nr`)\n-   `Project__c.Opportunity__c` (target) <- `proj.opp` (source, maps to `chancen.chance_id`)\n-   `Installed_Asset__c.Account__c` (target) <- `assets.kd_ref` (source, maps to `kunden.kunden_nr`)\n-   `Installed_Asset__c.Project__c` (target) <- `assets.projekt_ref` (source, maps to `proj.proj_id`)\n\nAll mappings for foreign keys will ensure consistency across tables, leveraging the defined primary key transformations.\n\n\"\"\"\nThis model transforms the `kunden` source table into the `Account` target table. It maps direct fields, applies `INITCAP` and `TRIM` for the `Name` field with a `COALESCE` for NOT NULL, and uses a `CASE` statement to map `kategorie` to the `Customer_Tier__c` enum. Unspecified date fields are set to NULL, and `IsDeleted` is hardcoded to 0 as per the plan."
